{"parentUuid":"db822e44-bb2e-4f5b-a87e-ff3131c96661","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"c93d3662-5462-4799-b6d7-cd0b2d4e2c75","agentId":"a15312ba4ecaf116c","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AUJ63vZh1U7dzF468iLNxN","type":"tool_result","content":"=== FORCE on usage_rollup anywhere? ===\nNO FORCE for usage_rollup\n=== all usage_rollup readers (are they inside scoped_transaction?) ===\nsrc/api/routes/usage_daily.py:2:for one UTC day, aggregated from the pre-computed `usage_rollup` counters.\nsrc/api/routes/usage_export.py:2:`usage_rollup` rows as an RFC 4180 CSV.\nsrc/api/routes/usage_export.py:32:        \"description\": \"The caller's usage_rollup rows as RFC 4180 CSV (header row always first).\",\nsrc/api/routes/usage_export.py:74:    \"\"\"Stream the caller's own `usage_rollup` rows as CSV, optionally\nsrc/db/session.py:7:PostgreSQL row-level-security policy on `events`/`usage_rollup` (defense in\nsrc/db/session.py:35:            # quotas row (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE) then reads usage_rollup in a\nsrc/db/session.py:58:async def scoped_transaction(api_key_id: int) -> AsyncIterator[AsyncSession]:\nsrc/db/README.md:34:  reads `usage_rollup` as a **separate** statement; that second read only sees the prior\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:1:\"\"\"Repository for reading `usage_rollup` — the O(1) aggregate lookup behind\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:27:async def find_usage_rollup(\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:43:            FROM usage_rollup\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:107:async def count_usage_rollups(\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:134:    count_sql = text(f\"SELECT count(*) FROM usage_rollup WHERE {where_clause}\")  # nosemgrep: python.sqlalchemy.security.audit.avoid-sqlalchemy-text.avoid-sqlalchemy-text\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:139:# Rows fetched per server-side-cursor round-trip in `stream_usage_rollups`.\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:147:async def stream_usage_rollups(\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:180:    # Safe: same invariant as count_usage_rollups — `where_clause` is fixed\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:187:        FROM usage_rollup\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:213:async def aggregate_daily_event_counts(\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:220:    \"\"\"Sum `usage_rollup.event_count` per `metric` over `[day_start, day_end)`,\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:222:    same invariant as `find_usage_rollup`/`count_usage_rollups`).\nsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py:235:            FROM usage_rollup\nsrc/repositories/quotas_repo.py:119:    total and all get admitted). Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own\nsrc/repositories/quotas_repo.py:144:            FROM usage_rollup\nsrc/repositories/README.md:11:| `events_repo.py` | `insert_event_if_new(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, returning `None` on a duplicate. `find_event_by_idempotency_key(session, *, api_key_id, idempotency_key)` — reads back the original row on a duplicate replay. `increment_usage_rollup(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start, quantity)` — the rollup upsert, called only after `insert_event_if_new` returns a row. |\nsrc/repositories/README.md:12:| `usage_repo.py` | `find_usage_rollup(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). `count_usage_rollups(api_key_id, customer_id=None, metric=None, window_from=None, window_to=None)` — the export's pre-flight row-cap count over the same optional filters. `stream_usage_rollups(api_key_id, ..., limit)` — the export's server-side-cursor stream (`session.stream(...)`, yields `UsageRollupExportRecord`), ordered by a **fixed literal** `ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` (never client-derived) with `LIMIT`. The count and stream queries share a `_export_filter_clause_and_params` helper so their WHERE clauses can never drift apart. |\nsrc/repositories/README.md:36:- `find_usage_rollup` returns only `{total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\nsrc/repositories/README.md:38:- `stream_usage_rollups` yields `UsageRollupExportRecord{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity}` — exactly the four exported columns, never `event_count`, `updated_at`, or `api_key_id`.\nsrc/repositories/README.md:63:- `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` deliberately issues the `FOR UPDATE` lock on `quotas` and the `usage_rollup` read as two separate statements, not a single `LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` query.\nsrc/repositories/README.md:65:- A single combined statement lets a waiter that queued before the holder committed read `usage_rollup` from its own stale pre-wait snapshot — verified empirically during implementation: every concurrent waiter read the same stale total and all got admitted, silently breaking the cap.\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:5:from `aggregate_daily_event_counts` (a DB error, a connection drop) propagates\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:18:from src.db.session import scoped_transaction\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:20:from src.repositories.usage_repo import aggregate_daily_event_counts\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:38:    async with scoped_transaction(principal.api_key_id) as session:\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:39:        records = await aggregate_daily_event_counts(\nsrc/services/usage_daily_service.py:50:        resource=\"usage_rollup\",\nsrc/services/usage_export_service.py:25:from src.db.session import scoped_transaction\nsrc/services/usage_export_service.py:27:from src.repositories.usage_repo import count_usage_rollups, stream_usage_rollups\nsrc/services/usage_export_service.py:58:    async with scoped_transaction(principal.api_key_id) as session:\nsrc/services/usage_export_service.py:59:        row_count = await count_usage_rollups(\nsrc/services/usage_export_service.py:95:    CSV-encode